          "body": "The arrest comes at the last possible moment. Abraham has bound Isaac, laid him on the altar atop the wood, stretched out his hand, taken the knife — and the Angel of the LORD calls from heaven *Abraham, Abraham!* The doubled name (cf. *Moses, Moses* — Exodus 3:4; *Samuel, Samuel* — 1 Samuel 3:10; *Saul, Saul* — Acts 9:4) marks the moment as a hinge of redemptive history. The verdict: *now I know that you fear God, since you have not withheld your son, your only son, from Me*. And then Abraham *raises his eyes* (the same idiom as 22:4) and sees what God has already prepared: a ram caught in the thicket by its horns. Isaac is unbound; the ram is bound; the ram dies in Isaac's place. This is the OT's clearest pre-Levitical picture of substitutionary atonement: the worshiper is spared because a substitute, provided by God Himself, takes his place on the altar. *YHWH-Yireh* — *the LORD will provide* — becomes the name of the mountain and the proverb of Israel."
