          "title": "The typology — Moriah looks forward to Calvary",
          "body": "Genesis 22 is the OT's most concentrated pre-figuring of the cross. Beloved only son (22:2; cf. John 3:16). Carrying wood up the mountain (22:6; cf. John 19:17). Three days under the shadow of death (22:4; cf. 1 Corinthians 15:4). Father willing to give the son (22:10; cf. Romans 8:32 — *He who did not spare His own Son*, an almost verbatim echo of *you have not withheld your son*). Substitute provided by God Himself (22:13; cf. John 1:29). And the same geographical complex: Moriah is Zion is the ridge that holds Calvary. The crucial difference: on Moriah the knife was stopped and a ram died in Isaac's place. On Calvary the knife was not stopped — *He who did not spare His own Son but delivered Him over for us all* — because no ram could substitute for the Son of God. Abraham received Isaac back *as a type* (Hebrews 11:19); the Father received the Son back in resurrection as the antitype."
